<p>
Values of <m>y_0</m> for which <m>f(y_0) = 0</m> are called <term>critical points</term>.  They provide <term>equilibrium</term> solutions of the autonomous equation <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = f(y)</m>.  That is, <m>y(x) \equiv y_0</m> are constant solutions.</p>

<p> Why are equilibrium solutions constant solutions?  Hint: Remember the result of the previous problem.  
</p>
</li>

