<li><p> Solution curves often approach equilibrium solutions as <m>x</m> increases, or move away as <m>x</m> increases.  This is called <term>stability</term>. </p> 
<ol>
<li><p> If all nearby solution curves approach <m>y_0</m>, then the equilibrium is called a <term>sink</term> (<term>stable</term>).  </p></li>
<li><p>  If at least some nearby solution curves do not approach <m>y_0</m>, then the equilibrium is called <term>unstable</term>.  </p></li>
<li><p>  If all nearby solution curves move away from <m>y_0</m>, then the equilibrium is called a <term>source</term> (unstable).  </p></li>
</ol>
<p> Determine the stability of the two equilibrium solutions <m>y_1(x) \equiv -1</m> and <m>y_2(x) \equiv 2</m> to the equation <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = y^2 - y - 2.</m> </p>
</li>
</ol>
</p>
